{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3d422674-f408-455d-9a25-66ef379f0190","content":"## Debugging a C# MCP Server with MCP Inspector\n\n**1. Start the Inspector:**\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\n\nThis opens a web UI (usually at `http://localhost:6274`).\n\n**2. Configure the connection:**\n\nIn the Inspector UI:\n- **Transport Type:** `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `run --project /path/to/YourMcpServer.csproj`\n\nOr if you have a published DLL:\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `/path/to/YourMcpServer.dll`\n\n**3. Click \"Connect\"** — the Inspector spawns your process and communicates over stdin/stdout.\n\n**4. Explore & test:**\n- **Tools tab** — lists discovered tools; invoke them with sample inputs.\n- **Resources / Prompts tabs** — test those if exposed.\n- The request/response log shows raw JSON-RPC messages for debugging.\n\n**⚠️ Key gotcha:** Your server must write MCP JSON-RPC **only** to stdout. Any `Console.WriteLine` debug logging will corrupt the protocol. Log to **stderr** instead:\n\n```csharp\nConsole.Error.WriteLine(\"debug info here\");\n```\n\nThe Inspector captures stderr separately and displays it in its log pane.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b2c8cc75-c08c-4e66-a844-cb03719cc29b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to connect a C# MCP server (using stdio transport) to the MCP Inspector for interactive testing/debugging. This is a knowledge question — I can answer directly without needing to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":380},"id":"b6e9a294-f001-49c0-bff3-0920fc1446ed","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:48:02.658Z","parentId":"bd4f6e1b-62b6-48af-a6bb-83f142176beb"}
